SIMPLE: lisp
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lisp
<hw>Lisp</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧sp)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Lisped</conjf> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧spt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Lisping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>lispen</ets>, <ets>lipsen</ets>, AS. <ets>wlisp</ets> stammering,
lisping; akin to D. & OHG. <ets>lispen</ets> to lisp, G.
<ets>lispeln</ets>, Sw. <ets>l⟦aum⟧spa</ets>, Dan.
<ets>lespe</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pronounce the sibilant
letter <xex>s</xex> imperfectly; to give <xex>s</xex> and <xex>z</xex>
the sound of <xex>th</xex>; -- a defect common among children.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To speak with imperfect articulation; to
mispronounce, as a child learning to talk.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As yet a child, nor yet a fool to fame,⟦br⟧
I <qex>lisped</qex> in numbers, for the numbers came.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To speak hesitatingly with a low voice, as if
afraid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lest when my <qex>lisping</qex>, guilty tongue should halt.</q>
<rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lisp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lisp
<hw>Lisp</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pronounce with a
lisp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter with imperfect articulation; to express
with words pronounced imperfectly or indistinctly, as a child speaks;
hence, to express by the use of simple, childlike language.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To speak unto them after their own capacity, and to
<qex>lisp</qex> the words unto them according as the babes and children
of that age might sound them again.</q> <rj><qau>Tyndale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To speak with reserve or concealment; to utter
timidly or confidentially; <as>as, to <ex>lisp</ex>
treason</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lisp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lisp
<hw>Lisp</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The habit or act of lisping. See
<er>Lisp</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>, 1.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I overheard her answer, with a very pretty <qex>lisp</qex>,
⟦ldquo⟧O! Strephon, you are a dangerous creature.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><au>Tatler.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>LISP</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: LISP
<hw>LISP</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧sp)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Computers)</fld>
<ety>[<ets>Lis</ets>t <ets>P</ets>rocessing.]</ety> <def>a high-level
computer programming language in which statements and data are in the
form of lists, enclosed in parentheses; -- used especially for rapid
development of prototype programs in artificial intelligence
applications .</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lisper</ent>⟦br⟧
